Pantheon Money Bin — Transparent Bias News Engine (TBNE) v1.0

Core Principle

Truth ≠ one voice
Truth ≈ many lenses + known weightings + shared evidence

⸻

1) System Architecture (clean + buildable)

Layer 1 — Raw Intake (Spider)
	•	Aggregate across:
	•	major outlets (left, right, intl.)
	•	primary sources (gov docs, filings, transcripts)
	•	direct media (videos, speeches, datasets)

👉 Rule:

Never summarize without storing the source

⸻

Layer 2 — Fact Extraction (Mirror + Hypatia)
	•	Extract:
	•	claims
	•	numbers
	•	timelines
	•	Tag each with:
	•	confidence
	•	source count
	•	contradiction flags

👉 Output:

“Fact Table” (not narrative yet)

⸻

Layer 3 — Bias Profiles (Conductor Layer)

This is your key idea.

Users can choose or define:
	•	“economic lens”
	•	“human impact lens”
	•	“national security lens”
	•	“libertarian / progressive / neutral weighting”

Each profile = ConstraintProfile

Example:

bias_profile = {
  economic_weight: 0.4,
  human_cost_weight: 0.3,
  long_term_risk: 0.2,
  emotional_language_penalty: 0.1
}

👉 Important:

Bias is declared, not hidden

⸻

Layer 4 — Narrative Generation (Dragonfly)

The system produces:
	•	multiple summaries of the same facts
	•	each under a different bias profile

👉 So instead of:

“here’s the news”

You get:

“here are 4 valid interpretations with explicit weightings”

⸻

Layer 5 — Comparison View (Hound + Mirror)
	•	Highlight:
	•	where narratives differ
	•	what facts are shared
	•	what is uncertain

👉 This is HUGE:

The delta between narratives is the insight

⸻

2) User Experience (this is what makes it work)

Instead of scrolling headlines:

You see:

Event: “X policy passed”
	•	✅ Confirmed facts
	•	⚠️ Disputed claims
	•	🔍 Missing info

Then:

View modes
	•	Neutral baseline
	•	Economic-heavy
	•	Human-impact-heavy
	•	Custom (user-defined)

⸻

3) Anti-Manipulation Design

You were right to worry about influence.

So bake in:

A. Source Transparency
	•	Every claim links to origin

B. Weighting Visibility
	•	Users see exactly how output was generated

C. Multi-Model Check
	•	run multiple models → compare outputs

D. Adversarial Pass (Hound)
	•	actively search for:
	•	propaganda patterns
	•	missing context
	•	statistical framing tricks

⸻

